The edamame saga continues in Guatemala @the.metreat

I’m not a long caption girl but when @lisahayim posted a story on her Instagram looking for a photographer— professional or hobby who would capture @the.metreat, but would also be a part of the experience I responded with, “me, I think?” 

I felt that the opportunity aligned perfectly with my skill set, but I was also nervous that I wouldn’t be good enough to do the job. In the time I’ve talked to Lisa on the internet I have always felt her acceptance, so I detached from the outcome and as we went over deliverables I realized my passport was expired. This of course added to the doubt of whether I should go or not. I ended up getting my Passport the day before I headed to Guatemala.

Thank you Lisa for trusting and believing that I could capture the experience. I am truly so grateful I was able to be there to be a part of this special trip. This group of women, staff included was a truly exceptional collection of humans. 

We talked about how we will never be able to explain what this experience was to anyone else,  but my hope is that when you look at these photos you to FEEL the joy, the experiences, the laughter, the pain, the bonds, the love, the grief, and the acceptance.

Here’s to creating for the story and not the hustle.
